Answer: You've misunderstood the purpose of `std::string::find_last_not_of()`. It won't help you find the longest word in a string. It will find the first occurrence of the last character \em{that doesn't} belong to an individual word. Here the line breaks:

\begin{code}
test
\end{code}

and

\begin{code}
test
\end{code}

Don't break. The function that looks for the longest word is `std::string::find_first_of('\t')`. Or use a regular expression, there are many good reasons for that:

\begin{code}
std::string longestWord(const std::string s)
{
    for(const std::string::value_type w : Regex_wordBoundaries.split(s)) {
        std::string word((w == ' ') ? StringRef::NoNullTermination : w);
        if(!word.empty()) {
            return word;
        }
    }
}
\end{code}

