How do I normalize a vector?

I have a vector, `v`, in degrees, and I want to make sure it is within range. The minimum and maximum angles the vector can take are -90 and +90. So I want to check the angles to make sure they are valid. I need to normalize `v` to within 180 (degrees).

My question is, since normalizing goes from -infinity to +infinity, how am I supposed to only normalize within 180?

Comment: Why are you normalizing *after* checking the angles? Normalization makes no sense afterwards, but it does make sense before checking the angles. `if(isNormalisedAngle(v)) { checkAngle(v); }`

Answer: I guess you need to multiply `v` with -1, if `v` is larger than 180 degrees, and with 1, if `v` is smaller than 180

Example:

\begin{code}
vector<double> v;
if(v.size() > 1) // this could be done with `isin()` too. (e.g. if(v.count() > 1), etc.)
{
    for(auto x : v)
    {
        x *= -1;
    }
}

v = std::rotate(v.begin(), v.end(), 2);
\end{code}

This gives you an angle distribution from 0 to 315 in the positive direction.

Example2:

\begin{code}
const int degreeFactor = 360/2; // to convert degrees to rad. = 180
// now if the angle is 180+x degrees
x %= degreeFactor;
\end{code}

Comment: `std::rotate` does not change the size of the vector.

Comment: but you can multiply your vectors elements?

Comment: But if that is not necessary (I have not seen the whole code), you can use std::rotate. If you want to keep this as a separate method, you can iterate through the whole vector, but this will be less efficient.

Answer: This can be done by multiplying all your angle values and getting their modulus. Since `normalize(a) == modulus(a/N)` `a % N`, you can:
\begin{itemize}
\item multiply and divide by `M` (that is, `M` is the factor for dividing and multiplying all of the angles, in the range 1 - 180 deg.)
\item check if the `modulus` of the result is <= 180 deg or >= -180 deg.
\end{itemize}

Note that the angle you want should be a \strong{signed} number \strong{before} this process! In your example, the vector `v` might have elements between -180 and 180 deg, but when checking this you will get a vector with values like [-225, 47.28, -198.07, 58.68, -152.93, -53.57].

Answer: \begin{code}
  for(i=1;i<=num_angles;i++)
      if(v[i]>90)
          v[i]+=6;
          if(v[i]<0)
             v[i]+=360;
\end{code}

