There are great options to collect texts from your daily experience, either by means of the web or by means of your own applications, the most used option is through the web. In our lab we use the Text Analytics Library (TAL)\footnote{\url{https://github.com/Microsoft/tal}}. TAL is a collection of tools, among them the Tweet Analyzer allows to extract text from the social media (\url{https://github.com/Microsoft/Twitter-Analytics}); it is based on the NLTK (Natural Language Toolkit)\footnote{\url{https://www.nltk.org/}} and it supports many popular social media services. The second most used option in our lab is to use custom applications. As a result of the first step, we will have a collection of sentences. These sentences have to be normalized to a common vector space format. The most used option in our lab is Semeval-2 Task 3:
\begin{quote}
\vspace{-6mm}
\begin{small}
\texttt{SENTIMENTS: SENT(2014-2015) TASK3 SUBTASKB: \textbf{Sentiment Extraction on Multilingual Documents}}
\end{small}
\vspace{-2mm}
\end{quote}
In this task, we were only allowed to use monolingual texts. Thus, we had to prepare texts in different languages. The main challenge of this subtask was related to the fact that the sentences were not of the same length and, thus, they had to be reformulated in a way that they all shared the same length and similarities. We can do some reformation, like removing some punctuations, in order to have all sentences with the same length and, consequently, the same vector space representation. The resulting sentences in the vector space should follow the distribution generated in the previous step. This means that sentences in similar language will be close to each other, while dissimilar languages will be separated by a wide gap.

In the following section, we explain the different steps, from the original text to the new reformulated sentence.

\subsection{Reformulation of Sentences}
\label{sec:reformulation}

\vspace{-2mm}
\begin{quote}
\vspace{-2mm}
\begin{small}
\texttt{P1. The text extracted for our task is in the following language: French, Dutch and German. In this task, only monolingual documents are allowed.}
\vspace{-6mm}
\end{small}
\end{quote}

\vspace{-3mm}
\begin{quote}
\vspace{-2mm}
\begin{small}
\texttt{P2. To deal with the problem of sentences with different lengths, }
\texttt{we may consider converting sentences to a common format.}
\vspace{-2mm}
\end{small}
\end{quote}

The first subpoint of this paragraph refers to the sentence structure, in this case, the sentences have different lengths. The solution to this problem is to use text representations which support text summarization, in our case, the Sentence Blobs (SBs) as presented by the \emph{TalkBank} project\footnote{\url{https://talkbank.org}}. An SB is a short text representation composed of the most frequent words. For more details, you can look at our paper \cite{OConnor_Rodriguez-Munoz_Correia:TAL2017}. The second subpoint indicates that a problem of the sentences is their length. Usually, short sentences have lower values and longer sentences have high values (\autoref{fig:vectors}), however, we need sentences in the same length.

