Answer: You should first check whether the target build number is zero by #ifdef:

\begin{code}
#if TARGET_BUILD_NUM_STRIP != 0
#error Wrong target build number
#endif
\end{code}

And then use #if defined to evaluate the target build number:

\begin{code}
#if TARGET_BUILD_NUM_STRIP == 0
#error Wrong target build number
#else
#endif
\end{code}

For more details, please refer to this link: https://stackoverflow.com/a/2967704/14510380

Answer: To answer your question, it's probably a good idea to understand what #ifdef and #ifdef do.

#ifdef "target-build" -- evaluates if target-build is defined, therefore it would be 1 if it were defined and 0 otherwise (if it isn't defined).

#ifndef is basically the opposite of #ifdef and will evaluate if target-build isn't defined, therefore it would be 0 if it were defined and 1 if it didn't.

So you should probably add #ifndef "target-build" and see if the resulting code looks different.

