To use it, you can create a JavaScript function that will send a request in the background; you do that by writing this code:

\begin{code}
var ajax = new XMLHttpRequest();
ajax.onreadystatechange = function() {
    if (ajax.readyState === 4 && ajax.status === 200) {
        // the request finished successfully; handle it here
    }
};
