To evaluate if the Transformer can generalize to other tasks we performed experiments on English constituency parsing. This task presents specific challenges: the output is subject to strong structural constraints and is significantly longer than the input. Furthermore, RNN sequence-to-sequence models have not been able to attain state-of-the-art results in small-data regimes.
Question: What is English constituency parsing?

Transformer-based models have shown strong results in this task \citep[e.g][]{Zhang:2019,Sachs:2019} and it's important to understand why their predictions are more accurate than that of other seq2seq models when it comes to parsing long sequences.

We experiment with a self-attention version of transformer and an encoder-decoder version, both followed by a CRF post-processing step. Since some of the outputs of the transformer-based model are very long, we use an additional linear projection layer to generate output length $= $500 tokens.

To train a transformer model, we create the input sequence from the POS representations from constituent level annotations and the corresponding tree-like syntactic parsing tree produced by a constituent parser \cite{Peters:2015,Sheng:2016}. Since not all constituent annotations provide the necessary level of information to accurately parse a sentence, we remove sentence-level annotations. We then pretrain the transformer on a 50 million corpus of English text and obtain a tokenizer model, a sequence-to-sequence pretraining and finetuning model. We also pretrain the transformer on 6.5 million SICK sentences and use it to generate the sequence-to-sequence model, which we will call Transformer-SICK. \footnote{Our pretraining and finetuning setup can be found in Appendix.}

To evaluate if our system generalizes, we obtain 10 SICK-8K development sets where the original constituency tree for each sentence was annotated with gold dependency structure. Our goal is to compare the performance of the Transformer-SICK model to the performance of a CRF-decoder model fine-tuned on the dev data. For this purpose, we use a two-stage decoding method which makes use of the predictions of the LSTM encoder to initialize the beam search process. We use beam size of 3 (the maximum output length was 195 tokens so this is reasonable) and set the minimum length at 15.

We use the standard evaluation metric of SICK of \textit{accuracy-no-edge} and \textit{accuracy-all-edges}, which is a percentage of correctly aligned trees that don't have any edge errors. Since we also obtain a tree in the same way as the CRF, we compute the difference between the CRF tree and the decoding tree to be able to get an evaluation of the decoding step.

