Create a short, concise summary of the paper based on its abstract.

Few-shot learning (FSL) is one of the key future steps in machine learning and raises a lot of attention. In this paper, we focus on the FSL problem of dialogue understanding, which contains two closely related tasks: intent detection and slot filling. Dialogue understanding has been proven to benefit a lot from jointly learning the two sub-tasks. However, such joint learning becomes challenging in the few-shot scenarios: on the one hand, the sparsity of samples greatly magnifies the difficulty of modeling the connection between the two tasks; on the other hand, how to jointly learn multiple tasks in the few-shot setting is still less investigated. In response to this, we introduce FewJoint, the first FSL benchmark for joint dialogue understanding. FewJoint provides a new corpus with 59 different dialogue domains from real industrial API and a code platform to ease FSL experiment set-up, which are expected to advance the research of this field. Further, we find that insufficient performance of the few-shot setting often leads to noisy sharing between two sub-task and disturbs joint learning. To tackle this, we guide slot with explicit intent information and propose a novel trust gating mechanism that blocks low-confidence intent information to ensure high quality sharing. Besides, we introduce a Reptile-based meta-learning strategy to achieve better generalization in unseen few-shot domains. In the experiments, the proposed method brings significant improvements on two datasets and achieve new state-of-the-art performance.
\end{abstract}

\section{Introduction}
The past decade has witnessed the growing use of artificial intelligence (AI) in many aspects of people's daily life. As one of the core building blocks of AI, machine learning (ML) contributes to a variety of applications, e.g., speech recognition, vision recognition, recommendation systems. Nowadays, chatbots are emerging as a key paradigm of dialogue systems, which has been rapidly utilized in various scenarios \cite{wu-etal-2020-unsupervised}. Specifically, dialogue systems receive natural language input directly from users and output a response. Since such user input can be arbitrary and complex, dialogue systems require great intelligence to understand them correctly for the proper generation of spoken response. To this end, dialogue systems can be divided into two categories: task-oriented dialogue systems and chitchat dialogue systems \cite{gupta-etal-2020-chitchat}. Chitchat dialogue systems aim to generate responses spontaneously from users' input, while task-oriented dialogue systems are used to complete specific tasks from end-users. A major part of chitchat systems is used for information searching, e.g., restaurant recommendation. Such systems usually only use a small set of open-domain dialogues, making them susceptible to domain-shift and also hard to train. On the other hand, task-oriented systems rely heavily on specialized industrial API to perform a certain task. As the number of APIs increases, the data requirement for learning the API knowledge and the domain-shift becomes difficult to meet. To address such complex and sparse scenarios, few-shot learning (FSL) has been proposed to achieve good or even better performance in few-shot settings. FSL can be regarded as the transfer learning (TL) variant for few-shot tasks, which can also be viewed as a generalization of single-task learning (STL) \cite{liang-etal-2018-multiple}. Due to the sparsity of data for few-shot tasks, it is common to use unsupervised methods to generate pseudo labels for few-shot tasks in FSL. Following this process, large amounts of pseudo labels can be generated from massive labeled datasets \cite{liang-etal-2018-multiple,zhang2017learning}. Then, these pseudo labels are utilized to train few-shot tasks.

Due to the limited data availability, the few-shot scenario requires that a dialogue-understanding system should have sufficient training data to learn relevant tasks. However, a fully labeled dialogue data is usually not available. In this paper, we focus on intent detection and slot filling which are two closely related tasks with a bidirectional relation. For instance, if the dialogue system is asked to find all restaurants located where a user is currently, both intents, \textit{location} and \textit{eating}, will be fired, however they are highly correlated. By combining the two tasks of intent detection and slot filling, we make the model focus on the correlation between intents and slots, and thus

